---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro'
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro'
---

<Layout title="Get Started — CrashGuard.io">
  <SiteHeader />
  <main class="pt-16">
    <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pt-24 pb-12 text-center">
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">Get Started</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-gray-400">
        <span class="text-green-500 font-semibold">CrashGuard</span> ships as a single Docker image containing the
        Engine API and the Admin App. Pull it, run it, and you're tracking canaries in minutes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">1. Pull the image</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-gray-400">
        The image is published to Docker Hub on every release.
      </p>
      <pre class="mt-4 bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-200"><code>docker pull russellcurry/crashguard.io:latest</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">2. Run it</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-gray-400">
        The container exposes two ports: <code class="text-green-500">80</code> for the Admin App (nginx) and
        <code class="text-green-500">5050</code> for the Engine API. Map them to whatever host ports you'd like:
      </p>
      <pre class="mt-4 bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-200"><code>docker run -d \
  --name crashguard \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -p 8050:5050 \
  -v crashguard-data:/data \
  russellcurry/crashguard.io:latest</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-400">
        Once it's running, open <code class="text-green-500">http://localhost:8080</code> for the Admin App. Point
        your services at <code class="text-green-500">http://localhost:8050</code> to create, checkpoint, and
        resolve canaries.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pb-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">3. Persisting data</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-gray-400">
        <span class="text-green-500 font-semibold">CrashGuard</span> stores everything in a SQLite database at
        <code class="text-green-500">/data/crashguard.db</code> inside the container. That path is declared as a
        Docker volume, so your data survives container restarts and recreation <span class="text-white">even if you
        don't specify a volume yourself</span> — Docker will create an anonymous one for you.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-400">
        Mounting your own data directory is optional, but recommended — it makes the database easy to find, back
        up, or move to a new host:
      </p>
      <pre class="mt-4 bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-200"><code>docker run -d \
  --name crashguard \
  -p 8080:80 \
  -p 8050:5050 \
  -v /home/me/crashguard-data:/data \
  russellcurry/crashguard.io:latest</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-400">
        Either way, <span class="text-white">don't run with <code class="text-green-500">--rm</code></span> if you
        rely on the anonymous volume — removing the container without a named or bind-mounted volume can leave you
        without an easy way to locate your data afterward.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pb-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">4. docker-compose, if you prefer</h2>
      <pre class="mt-4 bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm text-gray-200"><code>services:
  crashguard:
    image: russellcurry/crashguard.io:latest
    ports:
      - "8080:80"
      - "8050:5050"
    volumes:
      - crashguard-data:/data

volumes:
  crashguard-data:</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-400">
        Run it with <code class="text-green-500">docker compose up -d</code>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 pb-24">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">5. Set the admin portal URL</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-gray-400">
        Open the Admin App and go to <span class="text-white">Settings</span>, then set
        <span class="text-white">Admin portal URL</span> to whatever address you actually use to reach it in your
        browser — in the examples above, that's <code class="text-green-500">http://localhost:8080</code>.
      </p>
      <img
        src="/cg-admin-portal-settings.png"
        alt="The CrashGuard Admin App Settings page, with the Admin portal URL field set and an explanation of why it's needed"
        width="1077"
        height="773"
        class="mt-4 w-full h-auto rounded-lg border border-gray-700 opacity-0 transition-opacity duration-300"
        loading="eager"
        decoding="async"
        onload="this.classList.remove('opacity-0')"
      />
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-400">
        This isn't optional cosmetics — alerts (Slack, email, etc.) use it to link directly to the canary that
        triggered them. Without it, alerts have no way to point you anywhere useful.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-4 text-gray-400">
        The Engine can't figure this out on its own. It runs in the same container as the Admin App, behind an
        internal reverse proxy, so it only ever sees its own internal ports — it has no visibility into whatever
        host port you mapped with <code class="text-green-500">-p</code> when you started the container. If you
        remap ports (as in the examples above, where <code class="text-green-500">80</code> is exposed as
        <code class="text-green-500">8080</code>), this field is the only place that mapping is recorded — leave it
        blank and alerts simply omit the link rather than guess wrong.
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
